{
  "title": "Typography",
  "href": "http://www.google.com/design/spec/style/typography.html",
  "content": [
    {
      "type": "intro",
      "html": "<p>Since the Ice Cream Sandwich release, Roboto has been the standard typeface on Android. Since Froyo, Noto has been the standard typeface on Android for all languages not covered by Roboto. Noto is also the standard typeface for all languages on Chrome OS.</p>"
    },
    {
      "type": "article-list",
      "articles": [
        {
          "type": "article",
          "title": "Language categorization",
          "modules": [
            {
              "type": "module",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "module-body",
                  "html": "<p>Language scripts can be divided into three categories:</p><p><strong>English and English-like</strong>: Latin (except Vietnamese), Greek, and Cyrillic scripts, supported by both Roboto and Noto. Roboto has been extended to completely cover all Latin, Greek, and Cyrillic characters as defined in Unicode 7.0. The number of supported characters has doubled from previous releases, from about 2000 to about 4000 characters.</p><p><strong>Tall</strong>: Language scripts that require extra line height to accommodate larger glyphs, including South and Southeast Asian and Middle-Eastern languages, like Arabic, Hindi, Telugu, Thai, Vietnamese. Noto supports these languages with two weights.</p><p><strong>Dense</strong>: Language scripts that require extra line height to accommodate larger glyphs, including Chinese, Japanese, and Korean. Noto supports these languages with seven weights.</p><p>See the full list in the <a href=\"http://www.google.com/design/spec/style/typography.html#typography-language-categories-reference\">language categories table</a>.</p>"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "article",
          "title": "Typeface",
          "modules": [
            {
              "type": "module",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "module-body",
                  "html": "<p>Roboto has been refined extensively to work across the wider set of supported platforms. It is slightly wider and rounder, giving it greater clarity and making it more optimistic. </p>"
                },
                {
                  "type": "figure-group",
                  "figures": [
                    {
                      "type": "figure",
                      "mediaType": "image",
                      "src": "media/publish/material_v_4/material_ext_publish/0Bx4BSt6jniD7SW9CUzR4MnRpOTg/style_typography_roboto1.png",
                      "caption": "<p>Examples of Roboto</p>"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ],
              "title": "Roboto"
            },
            {
              "type": "module",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "module-body",
                  "html": ""
                },
                {
                  "type": "figure-group",
                  "figures": [
                    {
                      "type": "figure",
                      "mediaType": "image",
                      "src": "media/publish/material_v_4/material_ext_publish/0Bx4BSt6jniD7Y3JIMkV5ZmVaM2c/style_typography_roboto2.png",
                      "caption": "<p>Roboto A-Z and numerals</p>"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "module",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "module-body",
                  "html": "<h4>Roboto font weights</h4><p>Roboto has six weights: Thin, Light, Regular, Medium, Bold, and Black. </p>"
                },
                {
                  "type": "figure-group",
                  "figures": [
                    {
                      "type": "figure",
                      "mediaType": "image",
                      "src": "media/publish/material_v_4/material_ext_publish/0Bx4BSt6jniD7ZHlGSHpsMjU5YmM/style_typography_weights1.png",
                      "caption": "<p>Roboto font weights</p>"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "module",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "module-body",
                  "html": "<p>Noto&#x2019;s vertical metrics are compatible with Roboto.</p>"
                },
                {
                  "type": "figure-group",
                  "figures": [
                    {
                      "type": "figure",
                      "mediaType": "image",
                      "src": "media/publish/material_v_4/material_ext_publish/0B_udO5B8pzrzcWkwSW11bkstZEU/style_typography_noto1.png",
                      "caption": "<p>Noto Sans examples for English and CJK (Chinese, Japanese, and Korean)</p>"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ],
              "title": "Noto"
            },
            {
              "type": "module",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "module-body",
                  "html": ""
                },
                {
                  "type": "figure-group",
                  "figures": [
                    {
                      "type": "figure",
                      "mediaType": "image",
                      "src": "media/publish/material_v_4/material_ext_publish/0B_udO5B8pzrzOEh3Z1BUNFdsVGc/style_typography_noto2.png",
                      "caption": "<p>Noto Sans examples for Thai and Hindi (Devanagari)</p>"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "module",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "module-body",
                  "html": "<h4>Noto font weights</h4><p>Noto Sans CJK (Chinese, Japanese, and Korean) has seven weights: Thin, Light, DemiLight, Regular, Medium, Bold, and Black. The weight of Noto Sans CJK Regular is the same as Roboto Regular. </p>"
                },
                {
                  "type": "figure-group",
                  "figures": [
                    {
                      "type": "figure",
                      "mediaType": "image",
                      "src": "media/publish/material_v_4/material_ext_publish/0B_udO5B8pzrzdFA4NUh2TG1rT1E/style_typography_weight1.png",
                      "caption": "<p>Noto Sans CJK font weights</p>"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "module",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "module-body",
                  "html": "<p>Noto fonts for Thai, Devanagari, and all other major living languages have Regular and Bold weights.</p>"
                },
                {
                  "type": "figure-group",
                  "figures": [
                    {
                      "type": "figure",
                      "mediaType": "image",
                      "src": "media/publish/material_v_4/material_ext_publish/0B_udO5B8pzrzdTRNVG0yX3JkUEE/style_typography_weight2.png",
                      "caption": "<p>Noto Sans Thai and Hindi (Devanagari) font weights</p>"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "module",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "module-body",
                  "html": "<p>Hints are the instructions embedded in a font on how to modify (distort) a glyph to look better on low-resolution displays. As a tradeoff, a hinted font consumes more space than the unhinted version.</p><p>Both Roboto and Noto have hinted and unhinted versions. Google recommends: </p><ul><li>Use the unhinted versions on Android and on Mac OS X, which doesn&#x2019;t implement hints. </li><li>Use hinted fonts on Chrome OS, Windows, and Linux.</li></ul>"
                }
              ],
              "title": "Hinted fonts"
            },
            {
              "type": "module",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "module-body",
                  "html": "<p>For both Android and web properties, the font stack should specify Roboto, Noto, and then sans-serif.</p>"
                }
              ],
              "title": "Font stack"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "article",
          "title": "Styles",
          "modules": [
            {
              "type": "module",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "module-body",
                  "html": "<p>Too many type sizes and styles at once can wreck any layout. A typographic scale has a limited set of type sizes that work well together along with the layout grid.</p><p>These sizes and styles were developed to balance content density and reading comfort under typical usage conditions. Type sizes are specified with sp (scaleable pixels) to enable large type modes for <a href=\"http://www.google.com/design/spec/usability/accessibility.html\">accessibility</a>. </p>"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "module",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "module-body",
                  "html": "<p>Latin, Greek, and Cyrillic.</p><p>The basic set of styles are based on a typographic scale of 12, 14, 16, 20, and 34. </p>"
                },
                {
                  "type": "figure-group",
                  "figures": [
                    {
                      "type": "figure",
                      "mediaType": "image",
                      "src": "media/publish/material_v_4/material_ext_publish/0Bzhp5Z4wHba3alhXZ2pPWGk3Zjg/style_typography_styles_scale.png"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ],
              "title": "English and English-like scripts"
            },
            {
              "type": "module",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "module-body",
                  "html": ""
                },
                {
